.\" %W% %G%
.TH Dnew 2D D-language
.SH NAME
Dnew \- To create new windows on the monitor
.br
.I (D Language Tool)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B Dnew
.fI "[name [bottom top left right]]"
.br
.B Dnew
[option\*=\fIvalue\fR] [option\*=\fIvalue\fR] ...
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Dnew 
creates new graphics windows on the graphics monitor.
Options are
.ns
.TP 
.RI name\*= name
Name to be assigned to newly created window.  If the user provides
no name,
.I Dnew
will generate a unique name.
.br
.ns
.TP 
.RI top\*= number
Sets the vertical coordinate of the top of the window to the specified
.I number.
.br
.ns
.TP 
.RI bottom\*= number
Sets the vertical coordinate of the bottom of the window to the specified
.I number.
.br
.ns
.TP 
.RI left\*= number
Sets the horizontal coordinate of the left of the window to the specified
.I number.
.br
.ns
.TP 
.RI right\*= number
Sets the horizontal coordinate of the right of the window to the specified
.I number.
.br
.PP
Coordinates use a percentage scale; values are in the range 0-100 with the
coordinate 0,0 being the lower left corner of the screen.
.PP
.I Dnew
runs interactively if window coordinates are not provided on the command line.
It uses the pointing device (mouse) to construct the new window, and returns
the name of the new window upon completion (usually a number).  \fIDnew\fR
can be used to create multiple windows on the monitor;  these windows can
overlap.  Note, however, that \fIDnew\fR will not \fIchoose\fR a window
for display of graphics (see \fIDchoose[2D]\fR).
.PP
\fIDnew\fR exits with the name of the new window.  A unique name is
also given to the window if not specified on the command line.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.TS
ll.
\fIDINTRO[2D]\fR	Introduction to the GRASS \fID\fR tools
.br
.sp
\fIDchoose[2D]\fR	To choose a window in which to display graphics
.br
\fIDclear.screen[2D]\fR	To clear all windows from the monitor, and from memory
.br
\fIDerase[2D]\fR	To erase the contents of the current window
.TE
.SH "AUTHOR"
James Westervelt, U.S. Army Construction Engineering Research Laboratory
